td: T Pallidum Antibodies (Syphilis IgG/IgM) (test code = CD:1122338461)

td._VALUE:
The detection of treponemal antibodies may indicate recent, past or successfully treated syphilis. This test cannot distinguish between active and treated infection, and therefore, may not be used to determine response to therapy, relapse, or reinfection.
A negative test result does not completely rule out the possibility of an infection with syphilis. Serum or plasma samples from the very early (pre-seroconversion) phase or the late phase of a syphilis infection can occasionally yield negative findings.
Reactive treponemal test results alone are not a diagnosis of syphilis. All REACTIVE results will be sent for RPR confirmation by a referral laboratory. If RPR confirmation results are discordant from initial antibody screen, CDC recommends an alternate method such as Treponema pallidum particle agglutination (TP-PA) be performed.  This third test will be performed automatically on all specimens with discordant results.
0
Samples should not be taken from patients receiving therapy with high biotin doses (i.e. > 5 mg/day) until at least 8 hours following the last biotin administration.

Hepatitis C Virus Ab Interp (test code = PN0001069)

td._VALUE:
Current methods for the detection of antibodies to HCV may not detect all infected individuals. A non-reactive test result does not exclude the possibility of exposure to HCV. The detection of anti-HCV antibodies indicates a present or past infection with hepatitis C virus, but does not differentiate between acute, chronic or resolved infection. For diagnostic purposes, the results should always be assessed in conjunction with the patients medical history, clinical examination and other findings.
0

td._VALUE:
The detection of treponemal antibodies may indicate recent, past or sucessfully treated syphilis. This test cannot distinguish between active and treated infection, and therefore, may not be used to determine response to therapy, relapse, or reinfection.
A negative test result does not completely rule out the possibility of an infection with syphilis. Serum or plasma samples from the very early (pre-seroconversion) phase or the late phase of a syphilis infection can occasionally yield negative findings.
All REACTIVE results will be sent for RPR confirmation by a referral laboratory. If RPR confirmation results are discordant from initial antibody screen, CDC recommends an alternate method such as Treponema pallidum particle agglutination (TP-PA) be performed.
